Saoul de corruption
My friend Boris was leaving my place, drunk.
I therefore suggested that he shouldn't drive.
He asked me why.
« You've had too much to drink », I said to him, « aren't you afraid of the police? »
Boris replied: « No, I have a document featuring Benjamin Franklin, it always comes in handy. »
He showed me his driver's license with a $100 bill slipped beside it.
Obviously, I knew the police took bribes, but I was worried that Boris might meet an honest officer.
« Impossible », declared Boris, « to get into the traffic police department, you have to buy your boss's silence.
If you don't take a bribe, how can you buy your boss's silence? »
Half of the drivers in Moscow use illegally purchased driver's licenses.
The fools who try to do things by the rules drown in administrative hassle.
By paying 100 dollars, you can drive around the city without brakes!
Corruption and misappropriation of funds have always existed in Russia, before and after Lenin's October Revolution.
But never at the record levels we see today.
All accept bribes, everywhere and for everything.
The only ones who don't accept them are those to whom none are offered, according to Boris.
Corruption flourishes in most institutions, and the fight against corruption always ends in a catastrophe or abandonment.
The police, prosecutors, customs officers, and even the Kremlin: no one, anywhere, is immune.
Recently, I was visiting a dacha village in one of the most beautiful suburbs of Moscow.
It was a luxurious place but similar to the gulag with its high security fences and guards.
Looking at the pretentious houses decorated with such little taste, I asked who owned them and heard myself reply that one of them belonged to an assistant mayor of Moscow, another to a famous singer, another to the son of the Moscow prosecutor.
But the most attractive property belonged to a modest tax service official.
Corruption now represents a more serious threat to Russia than the Chechen war.
In fact, the Chechen war would not have lasted as long if it had not been conducted by corrupt generals, officers, officials, and police who sell weapons and supplies to the rebels.
Russian television recently showed a bus shuttling between Grozny and Moscow, the same bus that brought to Moscow the 120 kilograms of explosives used for the Dubrovka theater siege, where so many victims perished during the operation to free the hostages.
A passenger on the bus covered the explosives with a cloth soaked in acid to prevent the customs dogs from detecting them.
A completely useless precaution.
No one controls the buses anymore today.
The driver, who didn't know what he was transporting, said he was stopped 50 times along the way, and always for the same reason.
A policeman would come to ask him: « Do you know the price? », and the driver would reply: « Of course, I know it », paying the bribe before leaving.
Without a bribe, the bus would have been delayed for hours at each stop, meaning days for the entire trip.
The war against Chechnya continues without end not only because the Chechen rebels have allies in Al Qaïda and all « the international terrorist network », but also because Russian corruption is their ally.
The police, the army, civilians who accept bribes, and thieves, who first tax Chechen civilians or simply steal their belongings, sell weapons and explosives to the terrorists, maps indicating where the minefields are, and provide the rebels with forged documents.
In May of this year, during the explosions in Kaspiisk, the terrorists used weapons purchased from Russian army officers.
The rebels have modern weapons.
Where do they come from?
In the mountains where the rebels hide, there are no gun shops.
But the 80,000 Russian soldiers fighting the rebels have, themselves, stockpiles of ammunition, from which the weapons are stolen and sold.
And not only weapons: some young officers sell their own men into slavery.
Russian corruption has reached catastrophic levels, yet no campaign has been launched against this plague.
Punish corruption more severely?
This would only increase the cost of corruption.
The harsher the punishment, the more one must pay to avoid it.
No official wants to fight corruption because they are themselves corrupt.
Ainsi, ceux que l'on appelle « les gens simples » considèrent ce phénomène avec bienveillance.
Ils disent de leur maire « oui bien sûr, il vole, mais regardez tout ce qu'il a fait pour la ville ! »
Les gens ordinaires n'aiment pas non plus les travailleurs honnêtes.
Pourquoi ?
Un billet de train coûte 100 roubles, mais en versant un petit pot-de-vin, on peut voyager pour 50 roubles.
The traveler and the conductor both benefit from this system.
An honest old grandmother told me one day that she had bought a ticket and tried to board the train.
The conductor stopped her, saying that passengers with a ticket were not allowed on the train!
For millions of Russians, corruption is a normal way of life.
If you don't want your son to be called up for military service, buy a military clerk who will strike his name off the list, or bribe a doctor to declare him unfit for any military activity.
You can enter any faculty for a certain price, regardless of your references and diplomas.
You can drive drunk, speed, ignore red lights, as long as Ben Franklin is there to offer himself to the police.
Alexander Menchikov, the minister of Peter the Great, understood the impossibility of winning the fight against corruption.
When the tsar Peter, disgusted by the corruption in Russia, decided to hang his corrupt officials, Menchikov replied: "Your Majesty, you risk losing all your subjects."
Since then, the situation has worsened.
Eliminating corruption might leave the State without citizens, but if we do not stop the spread of corruption, the citizens will soon be left without a State.
